I will generally try to avoid spoilers if I am interested in the development in a show, movie or book, but in general, I don't mind too much. I figure there are more important things to worry about than being caught up in what's happening in a fictional universe. In my mind, I'm going to find out anyway, so learning about an important plot development in advance doesn't affect me too much.
I thought about basic principles of storytelling and made assumptions that the filmmaker would try to follow typical convention to build up a story instead of jumping from scene to scene

I think I care less about spoilers nowadays than I did in the past. When you have lots of free time, you want to take the time to figure things out yourself rather than having the plot developments being told to you. When you get older and are more strapped for time, spoilers matter less because it helps you to get caught up with everything without having to spend the time yourself. For instance, you might seek out spoilers because it helps you to quickly catch up with what others are interested in, thus giving you something to discuss with your peers. An example would be like how people who don't care about football will still watch the Superbowl so that they don't feel left out the following day when everyone else is talking about it. Or how people will read about what happened in Game of Thrones without watching it because they want to feel part of what everyone else is watching.

I seek out trailers to give me an idea of what the movie will be about and see if I might be interested in it. It's the same as if you were to read a blurb about a book you want to read: you need some information to make a decision, but you wouldn't want to find out the entire story through the blurb.
I prefer to have the surprise of a revelation, but more oft than not, the presentation of something is as important as the content itself, so I generally don't care if something is spoiled either.
I wouldn't really call my imagination a strategy. Just guessed.
